s undesirable based on their supposed susceptibility to mental, moral, and physical defects. In this transformative book, Baynton argues that early immigration laws were a cohesive whole—a decades-long effort to find an effective method of excluding people considered to be defective. This effort was one aspect of a national culture that was increasingly fixated on competition and efficiency, anxious about physical appearance and difference, and haunted by a fear of hereditary defect and the degeneration of the American race.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEugenicszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aImmigrantsxMedical examinationszUnited States. 0aPeople with disabilitiesxLegal status, laws, etczUnited States. 0aPeople with disabilitiesxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aeugenics, disability, public health, immigration, population control, race, ethnicity, "as, undesirable, defective, exclusion, national identity, competition, capitalism, deafness, blind, epilepsy, mobility, scoliosis, disease, hernias, club feet, asylum, lgbtq, queer theory, intersexual, lameness, mental illness, developmental delays, degeneration, heredity, medical examination, handicapped, dependent, independence, labor, laws, legislation, government policy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226364339423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226364339/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles